&lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/terms/enterprise/>
  rdf:type schema:Article ;
  schema:url &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/terms/enterprise/> ;
  schema:name "Enterprise" ;
  schema:description "An Enterprise is a triple (C, Γ, O) — a hard core C of constitutive commitments treated as non-negotiable by participants, a generative mechanism Γ by which the pursuit of current aims produces residues that constitute new aims, and an operative structure O of organized cooperative agents. The defining structure: an enterprise is a temporally open, aim-generative, organized activity — the closest formal analog to MacIntyre's practice, Lakatos's research programme, and Penrose's theory of the firm. An enterprise is not aim-terminated (unlike an endeavor or project); it does not have a predetermined terminal state. What gives it unity is not a single deliverable but a hard core of commitments that orients all activity and persists through complete turnover of personnel, aims, and structure. Etymology: Old French entreprendre (to undertake between) — the in-between of enterprise is the sustained inhabited interval between inception and an indefinite end." ;
  schema:datePublished "2026-03-20" ;
  schema:dateModified "2026-03-20" ;
  schema:about &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/terms/enterprise/> ;
